{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01Bvc1oqQYbaVVvwM2yuiMdo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze the knowledge file against the source file carefully.\n\n**Source file analysis:**\n\nThe source file contains these sections:\n1. \"UI標準2.11. 共通エラー画面の構成\" (h2 heading)\n   - Sub-section: \"共通エラー画面のテンプレートを変更したい\" (h3)\n2. \"UI標準3. UI部品 (UI部品カタログ)\" (h2 heading)\n   - Sub-section: \"UI部品の表示・挙動を修正したい\" (h3)\n3. \"開閉可能領域\" (h2 heading)\n   - Sub-section: \"精査エラー時の開閉可能領域の制御を変更したい\" (h3)\n\nSo there are 3 h2 headings and 3 h3 headings total. The knowledge file has 3 sections (s1, s2, s3) which matches the 3 h2 headings. The warning about \"Section count 3 < source headings 5\" seems to be counting both h2 and h3 headings separately, which would give us 6 total headings, not 5. Let me recount the source headings to verify the actual structure. I'm examining the RST markup structure more carefully now. The heading hierarchy is determined by which characters are used for underlining and overline — when a line has both overline and underline with dashes, that's a higher-level heading than one with just an underline. The equals signs indicate a different heading level than the dashes, so I need to map out which sections are h2 versus h3 based on this pattern. The automated check is flagging a mismatch—it says 3 sections but counts 5 headings in the source, though there are actually 6 total. The knowledge file is merging each h2 with its single h3 sub-section, which makes sense since the h2s provide context while the h3s contain the actual content. This structure seems appropriate for the document.\n\nNow I'm checking if any information got lost in the conversion. The first section preserves the key instruction about modifying files in the nablarch-template-error plugin. The second section includes tables covering UI components, widgets, and modification targets...\n\nLooking at the data